defaultThe structure &amp; governance of banks in Northern Irelanddefault&#xa0;
default1)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe four major high street banks operating in NI all are owned externally. 
default2)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLocal management
default has limited discretion and is more likely to be involved in administering Group /Corporate policy set in Dublin, Copenhagen or London/Edinburgh. 
default3)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCore policy making such as Group Credit Risk management/ IT infrastructure / capital allocation across busine
defaultss units/ customer segmentation &amp; marketing
default 
defaultpolicies 
defaultare all in effect set outside NI
default.
default 
default4)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThree of the four
default high street banks 
defaultare subject to EC/EU State Aid restructuring programmes restricting 
defaultor constraining their freedom of action at 
defaultpolicy making
default level
default.
default5)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAlthough Santander for example has a high street presence its NI business customers will have their accounts handled by business banking centres in Glasgow or Newport or London in exactly the same way as any other customer anywhere in the UK and su
defaultbject to exactly the same terms &amp; conditions, charges eligibility &amp; lending criteria. 
default6)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe major issue in NI banking is that, bar the Progressive Building Society, there are no locally headquartered 
defaultfinancial services business and therefore no local contro
defaultl of policy.
default7)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe NI banking market has traditionally operated on the basis of cross-border / all-Ireland structures. 
default8)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis model is 
defaultnow 
defaulteffectively dead 
defaultlargely
default for reasons of politics &amp;
default economic nationalism arising out of the need for EU/ECB funding to rescue both the Irish banks &amp; state. 
default9)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis situation arose out of a failure of regulation leading Irish banks to over-extend themselves 
defaultboth 
defaultdomestically &amp; externally.
default10)
default&#xa0; 
defaultThis mistake will no
defaultt be repeated, 
defaultpolitical and public opinion will not tolerate 
defaultregulators in ROI
default allowing the
default major 
defaulttax-payer rescued 
default‘pillar’ banks allocating scare capital to support business in 
defaultoutside the state
default a
defaultt the expense of business &amp; individuals within the state.
default11)
default&#xa0; 
defaultThere will 
defaultalso be political, business public &amp; social pressure on ROI banks to focus on their domestic market and support local economic growth and development. This is not a narrow political point. In the UK we see the mirror image of this in the withdr
defaultawal of RBS/Lloyds for example from overseas markets and market segments nationally &amp; internationally.
default12)
default&#xa0; 
defaultWe must also recognize the different political &amp; legislative trajectories within &amp; between the UK &amp; Ireland and specifically issues arising from 
defaultregulatory developments within the Eurozone sub-set of countries within the EU and the UK focus on re-negotiations/ opt-outs/ subsidiarity etc.
default13)
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe practical consequences for NI are likely to be concentration
default of banking in fewer players, l
defaultess choice, less 
defaultcompetition and higher costs. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe possible break-up of RBS/Ulster Bank.default&#xa0;default14)
default&#xa0; 
defaultResolution of this issue is not solely or even substantially in the hands of RBS management nor UK politicians - 
defaultsomething which seems almost entirely missing from much public debate! 
default15)
default&#xa0; 
defaultYou should note that the EC has recently allowed Bank of Ireland to retain an insurance operation in Republic of Ireland which it had previously decided should be disposed of as a cond
defaultition of State Aid. The EC rationale for this was that there were no realistic buyers for the business in the market.
default16)
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe quid pro quo is that BOI must shed its corporate &amp; business banking activities in GB either through run-down or by sale
default 
defaultalthough it i
defaults able to
default 
defaultretain
default 
defaultthose in NI.
default 
defaultThe NI businesses are now exposed in that there will be loss of scope &amp; scale in service provision.
default17)
default&#xa0; 
defaultIt should also be noted that the BoI is now focusing on serving 
defaultpersonal business only 
defaultin GB through Post Office Financial 
defaultServices (POFS)
default 
defaultdelivered through PO branches &amp; supported by centralised deposit &amp; lending administration and on-line banking
default 
default18)
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe precedent has also been set &amp; the next revision of State Aid for BoI (&amp; there will almost inevitably be one) could require 
defaultthe disposal of its NI corporate &amp; business banking. This would leave the rump of its personal business which could be serviced via POFS. 
default19)
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe bank stake in POFS is a saleable asset in the last resort &amp; is now a hostage to fortune in that disposal may be m
defaultandated by EC/EU. The possibility of BoI exiting NI is no longer unthinkable.
default20)
default&#xa0; 
defaultI cannot comment on the status of Allied Irish/First Trust businesses other than to note that there were apparently no buyers when the business was put on the market a number of 
defaultyears ago. Given that Allied Irish remains subject to EC/EU State Aids considerations then that business may also be vulnerable
default regardless of public positions taken by management.
default21)
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn this context the price of future State Aid approvals for RBS may well be 
defaultdisposal of at least 
defaultthe Ulster Bank business in RoI regardless of the ‘good bank/bad bank’ arguments propounded by politicians/RBS executive management/board.
default22)
default&#xa0; 
defaultEC rules cannot 
defaulthowever 
defaultprevent individual customers opting to remain with their 
defaultcurrent bank regardless of whether or not ’their branch’ is sold. 
default23)
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe best forward-looking solution would seem to be to encourage the full absorption of the Ulster Bank NI business into RBS proper w
defaulthere it would benefit from the full resources of RBS unmediated by a ‘local’ headquarters.
default24)
default&#xa0; 
defaultGiven the lack of buyers for more substantial branch networks being disposed of by
default both
default Lloyds &amp; RBS disposal 
defaultof the Ulster Bank business in NI would not seem to be 
defaulta realistic option.
