default26)
default&#xa0; 
defaultI regard these issues as being intimately linked. 
default27)
default&#xa0; 
defaultMy recollection is that the NI banks were never more than ‘bit players’ in national ’trade’
default bodies such as British Bankers Association/APACs etc.
default28)
default&#xa0; 
defaultGiven their scope &amp; scale they would tend to be policy takers rather than makers.
default29)
default&#xa0; 
defaultFor that reason I suspect that national initiatives would receive only ‘lip service’ - the minimum necessary &amp; no more.
default Stats will show that use of for example SFLGS by NI banks was pathetic
default,
default the preference being to focus on own in-house products rather than develop the processes &amp; practices &amp; staff training
default 
defaultnecessary to support such initiatives, 
defaultsuch lack of support 
defaultin t
defaulturn stifle
defaultd
default demand - a bit of a self-fulfilling prophecy in a sense!
default30)
default&#xa0; 
defaultMy understanding is that much business lending remains in effect asset backed lending
default, security over assets first then looking at profitability &amp; repayment capacity
default 
default31)
default&#xa0; 
defaultFor so long as there is a significant overhang of property, whether warehoused in 
defaultNAMA or elsewhere, then property values will remain under pressure and represent a significant constraint on business lending. 
default32)
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn these circumstances access to national init
defaultiatives based for example on partial Govt guarantees for otherwise unsecured 
default&amp; cash-flow based 
defaultbusiness lending will remain essential. 
default33)
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe overwhelming proportion of businesses
default 
defaultin NI are in the micro to small category and more likely to benefit from or re
defaultquire cash-flow based rather than asset backed lending. Past experience of SFLGS does not offer much comfort in this respect.
default34)
default&#xa0; 
defaultI think the point needs to be made that ‘SME’s’ are not a single market with common needs. 
default35)
default&#xa0; 
defaultMany SME’s in the micro to small categ
defaultory will be largely locally orientated with substantial demand for transaction handling services - cash/ cheques/card payments - which are expensive to provide and largely unprofitable for banks
default36)
default&#xa0; 
defaultAny borrowing requirements
default 
defaultwill be relatively small and only
default marginally profitable once all admin &amp; overhead costs are considered 
default37)
default&#xa0; 
defaultParadoxically many large businesses operating in NI will have similar profile - transaction-based needs for electronic payments of salaries &amp; wages, suppliers, &amp; receipt of payments wit
defaulth minimum local overnight balances with borrowings /deposits
default 
defaultlargely managed by corporate treasury &amp; held in GB based branches
default38)
default&#xa0; 
defaultBusinesses in the small to medium category are likely to have the more complex needs not just for transaction services but cash 
defaultflow lending (overdrafts) and capital investment (term loans/ equity/venture capital finance, trade related financing. 
default39)
default&#xa0; 
defaultThis should /could be a profitable mix for banks but unfortunately banks have spent the last 20 years or so paying extolling the virtues
default of relationship banking whilst at the same time promoting financial promiscuity - by which I mean offering stand-alone products to non-current account holders
default.
default40)
default&#xa0; 
defaultWhilst this promiscuity does bring competition to the market it also fractures the ‘relationshi
defaultp’ model with no 
defaultbank having a clear overall picture of business needs hence driving the imperative for asset based lending and even then there may be differing views as to which lender has prior claim over which assets, all of which acts to constrain lend
defaulting limits
default41)
default&#xa0; 
defaultThere is no excuse for excluding lending from the proposed post code reporting. How will direct banks with no physical presence in NI report their figures? 
default42)
default&#xa0; 
defaultIf Santander/Tesco/Sainsbury /M&amp;S/First Direct/ for example all report their UK 
defaultlending 
defaultby post code then the ’unclassified’ stuff could be considered NI by default (I know it won’t be that simple but deduction by exception is possible!) 
default43)
default&#xa0; 
defaultRegional lending data must be made available otherwise 
defaultpublic policy making 
defaultwill occur in a partial vacuu
defaultm and risks being uninformed. 
default44)
default&#xa0; 
defaultLikewise banks themselves will be acting in a vacuum, making assumptions about the potential market for financial services which may not be realistic (there are both upsides &amp; downsides to this)
default&#xa0;
defaultAccess to banking in rural codefaultmmunitiesdefault&#xa0;default45)
default&#xa0; 
defaultThis is I am afraid essentially yesterday’s issue.
default46)
default&#xa0; 
defaultBranches have been closing for years &amp; the trend - visible across the UK &amp; Europe - will continue and indeed is accelerating. I believe that recent stats based on research 
defaultb
defaulty a UK university confirm this but may not show that rural communities are being anymore affected by this than deprived urban communities.
default47)
default&#xa0; 
defaultIt needs to be recognized that t
defaulthe role of the branch has changed over the years, currently configured largely as ‘sa
defaultles outlets’ even that function is becoming redundant with much marketing/sales /account servicing being done remotely by phone /on-line or social media. Salaries &amp; wages &amp; benefits have been paid electronically for decades
default. It is stated Govt policy to enc
defaultourage payment into accounts – the basic bank account is an outrun of this. 
defaultFinancial inclusion policy is about bank accounts for all not dependence on cash transactions.
default48)
default&#xa0; 
defaultAn increasing number of transactions are by card &amp; card technology is changing almost
default by the day. No-one any more has a need to visit a branch
default49)
default&#xa0; 
defaultRecent entrants to the NI personal financial services market - Tesco, Sainsbury &amp; M&amp; S for example- use their supermarket outlets as service points.
default50)
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe example of the BOI /Post Office joint venture
default is relevant here with cash transactions available through Post Offices/ATM‘s etc, not branches.
default 
default51)
default&#xa0; 
defaultAll other services including accounting transaction processing, credit scoring for personal lending including mortgages, personal loans &amp; credit cards can be
default centralised &amp; handled remotely.
default52)
default&#xa0; 
defaultEven business lending seems increasingly based on ’credit scoring’ principles.
default53)
default&#xa0; 
defaultIt is strange to note however than in respect of investment advice ‘past performance is no guarantee of or guide to future performance’ whereas 
defaultbehaviour based credit 
defaultscoring relies precisely on extrapolating past performance to predict future behaviour
default54)
default&#xa0; 
default‘Relationship banking’ no longer seems to require face to face contact being replaced by contact by phone/internet/social media channels - the tra
defaultditional branch has no future and only a limited lifespan.
default55)
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe issue should really be about adapting to new reality rather than preserving the past.
